		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Richmond</placeName>&#44; <date>January 22.1849</date>.</p>
			<p><addressee>Revrd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Respected Friend&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(5)">It seems that<lb/> you have not read my letter as I intended &#38; that I<lb/> have alarmed you unnecessarily. I did not intend to<lb/> communicate the information that ll of your Claims<lb/> here were offsetted by <persName>Jacob Ezekiel&#39;s</persName> indebtedness<lb/> but that some were perhaps in that condition &#38; others<lb/> could not be collected from other causes inability deaths<lb/> &#38;c&#59; and also my remarks about your matters remaining<lb/> in <persName>Ezekiel&#39;s</persName> hands&#44; were not intended to charge him<lb/> with dishonesty&#44; but meant that your matters could not<lb/> prosper in the hands of such an agent&#44; who &#40;it is<lb/> evident to me&#41; has been very luke&#45;warm in your interest<lb/> to say the least. I have no doubt in the hands of some<lb/> enterprising person your interests could be largely aug&#45;<lb/>&#45;mented&#44; as I wrote in my previous letter. As regards<lb/> the claim you hold against me&#44; I did not wish to use<lb/> any plea to get off&#44; but was under the impression that<lb/> <persName>Ezekiel</persName> had given me credit for the amount and made<lb/> correct returns to you for the <sic>ammount</sic> for I feel fully satisfied that I<lb/> have paid him for some volumes of the Occident in cash<lb/> &#38; have his receipt&#44; but cannot put my hand on it at<lb/> this moment&#44; notwithstanding I will pay what I owe you<lb/> as it is hard for you to loose under either circumstances&#44;<lb/> <persName>Ezekiel</persName> owes me so much&#44; he can owe me a little more</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>I had some conversation with <persName>Mr. Isaac Hyneman</persName><lb/> to&#45;day&#44; who was one of the persons referred to in my<lb/> last&#44; who has been under the same impression as<lb/> myself as regards <persName>Ezekiel</persName> having given him credit for the<lb/> amount&#44; but says you shall not suffer by him &#38; that<lb/> he will pay his account excepting for the numbers&#44; which<lb/> he did not receive&#44; amounting to about 1 vol. In all. I will<lb/> authorize <persName>Mr. N. Ezekiel</persName> to allow him the amount he<lb/> wishes deducted. I will on to&#45;morrow get your matters<lb/> out of <persName>Jacob Ezekiels</persName> hands &#38; place them with your<lb/> Agent <persName>Mr. N. Ezekiel</persName>&#44; who I hope will make an efficient<lb/> one. The next Occidents you forward&#44; he wishes you to<lb/> send by Adams Express Serv&#59; direct to <persName>N. Ezekiel</persName> care of<lb/> <persName>Jacob A Levy</persName>. I will pay over to him the money I owe<lb/> &#38; will endeavour with <persName>Mr. N. E.</persName> to collect all I can<lb/> I have nothing of interest to communicate. Our Ball<lb/> in aid of the Hebrew School Fund takes place on the<lb/> <date>7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Feby.</date> <persName>Mrs. Myers</persName> the eldest daughter of <persName>Jos. Marx</persName><lb/> deceased died here on the <date>17<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> Inst.</p>
			<p>Hoping that you are in Health</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">I remain</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">your Friend</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Isaac A Levy</persName></p>
			<p>P. S. If you should hear of a suitable person to fill the<lb/> office of Hazan&#44; let me hear from you</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>371 Walnut Street</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
          
